<div class="markdown"><h2 id="Introduction:-modeling-with-PlantModules.jl">Introduction: modeling with PlantModules.jl</h2></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>As the name suggests, one of the most important goals of PlantModules is to enable the user to easily model plant growth in a <em>modular</em> manner. In order to achieve this, we will define our plant in function of a few sets of similarly behaving parts or "modules" for short. Parts of the same module can be similar on the structural - and on the functional level.</p><p>On the structural level, some examples are:</p><ul><li><p>An oak tree can be considered a repeating module in a forest.</p></li><li><p>A branch can be considered a repeating module in a tree.</p></li><li><p>A collenchyma cell can be considered a repeating module in a branch.</p></li></ul><p>On the functional level, on the other hand:</p><ul><li><p>Most structural modules of a tree (branches, leaves, root segments, etc.) contain water which will flow between them as dictated by hydraulic laws, which plays an important role in plant growth. All these structural modules share this same functional module. </p></li><li><p>One or more of the plant's structural modules will assimilate carbon through photosynthesis, while the others do not. On the cellular level, only cells containing chloroplasts should share this functional module.</p></li></ul><p>As such, the workflow to create a model in PlantModules boils down to defining these modules and how they interact.</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><h2 id="Example-problem-definition">Example problem definition</h2><p>For the first tutorial, we will model the response of a hypothetical tomato plant to different transpiration rates. In higher plants, an increase in transpiration rate causes a reduction in the water potential of the stem. This phenomenon can be explained by the cohesion-tension theory, which states that the water in plant vessels forms a continuous network through its strong cohesive forces, and pressure reductions caused by leaf transpiration cause pressure gradients throughout the entire network. We will verify here that our basic functional modules can capture this phenomenon.</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><h2 id="Defining-the-model">Defining the model</h2></div>


<div class="markdown"><h3 id="Structure">Structure</h3></div>


<div class="markdown"><h4 id="The-plant">The plant</h4><p>The first step in modeling our plant's growth is defining its structure. For the first tutorial, we'll consider a very simple example: a tine tomato plant with a small stem and two leaves.</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>PlantModules uses <strong>graphs</strong> to define the relationships between modules. As such, structural modules need to be implemented as graph nodes of some sort. We'll be using the graph implementation from <a href="https://virtualplantlab.com/stable/manual/Graphs/">the PlantGraphs</a> package for this tutorial, though <a href="nothinghere">any graph implementation can be used</a>.</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>For our example, we will define two structural modules: a <code>Stem</code> module and a <code>Leaf</code> module. We will give both modules an attribute <code>D</code>, which corresponds to the name of the variable expressing the dimensions of the structural module. This is a vector containing one to three numbers, depending on whether the plant part is modelled as a sphere, a cylinder or a cuboid. The Leaves will be represented as flat cuboids, while the stem will be represented as a cylinder.</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>struct Stem &lt;: Node end</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>struct Leaf &lt;: Node
    D::Vector
end</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><p>We now define the plant structure using a graph. By specifying the value of the attribute <code>D</code>, we can specify different initial sizes for the different plant parts. Note that the cylindrical stem only needs 2 values specified (radius and length), while the cuboid leaves need 3 values (length, width and thickness).</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>plant_graph = Stem() + Stem() +
    (Leaf([5.0, 3.0, 0.05]), Leaf([4.0, 2.5, 0.05]));</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>plotstructure(plant_graph)</code></pre>

<div class="markdown"><h4 id="The-environment">The environment</h4><p>Plants need an environment to grow in. For most plants, the most basic environmental compartments that need defining are the soil, from which the plant gets water and nutrients, and the air, with which the plant exchanges gasses. We can make these compartments as complex as we want, such as different soil compartments for different layers, but we will stick to one graph node for each for now.</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>struct Soil &lt;: Node end</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>struct Air &lt;: Node end</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>soil_graph = Soil();</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>air_graph = Air();</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><p>We also need to define the connections between these environmental modules and the plant. Sadly, connecting both leaf nodes to the air would introduce a cycle into our graph, which is something many plant-focused graph implementations do not support.</p><p>To overcome this, PlantModules allows the user to input multiple graphs and then specify how to connect them:</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>graphs = [plant_graph, soil_graph, air_graph];</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>intergraph_connections = [[1, 2] =&gt; (getnodes(plant_graph)[1], :Soil), [1, 3] =&gt; (:Leaf, :Air)];</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><p>The above syntax means: "connect the first node from <code>graphs[1]</code> to all Soil nodes from <code>graphs[2]</code>", and all <code>Leaf</code> nodes from <code>graphs[1]</code> to all <code>Air</code> nodes from <code>graphs[3]</code>. Note that the order matters! For example, <code>[1, 2] =&gt; (:Root, :Soil)</code> is not the same as <code>[2, 1] =&gt; (:Root, :Soil)</code>.</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>The full structural connection information can then be acquired by bundling the graphs and connections into the <code>PlantStructure</code> wrapper.</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>plantstructure = PlantStructure(graphs, intergraph_connections);</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>plotstructure(plantstructure)</code></pre>

<div class="markdown"><div class="admonition is-note"><header class="admonition-header">Note</header><div class="admonition-body"><p>For our tiny example plant, we only have one structural module that actually repeats, somewhat defeating the purpose of modelling in a modular manner: we may as well write this entire model out by hand! Rest assured, however, that the approach we're seeing here also works for larger plants, as we will see in the next tutorial.</p></div></div></div>


<div class="markdown"><h3 id="Function">Function</h3></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>Now that we have an idea of the plant's structural modules, we need to assign them some kind of functionality. <code>PlantModules</code> expresses these as sets of differential equations, implemented in <a href="https://docs.sciml.ai/ModelingToolkit/stable/">ModelingToolkit.jl</a>. Assigning functionality then comes down to writing out the desired functional processes as <code>ModelingToolkit</code> models (or choosing them out from the prebuilt ones), mapping them to the structural modules, and finally specifying the initial- and parameter values for the different components of the system.</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><h4 id="Defining-functional-modules">Defining functional modules</h4></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>There are two types of functional module: next to the typical functional modules describing the function of a structural module, there are also the connection modules that describe how different structural modules are connected. Both are defined as <code>ModelingToolkit.jl</code> models. For this tutorial, we will limit ourselves to using functional modules already implemented in <code>PlantModules.jl</code>; implementation of new processes will be discussed in the second tutorial.</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>We list the pre-implemented functional modules here with a short description of each.</p><ul><li><p>Hydraulics</p><ul><li><p><code>hydraulic_module</code>: describes the hydraulics-driven growth of a compartment.</p></li><li><p><code>environmental_module</code>: describes a compartment that is subject to hydraulic laws but does therefor not change in size.</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Carbon dynamics</p><ul><li><p><code>constant_carbon_module</code>: describes a compartment with a constant amount of carbon.</p></li><li><p><code>simple_photosynthesis_module</code>: describes a compartment with carbon being produced during day and consumed proportionally to its concentration.</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Total water potential</p><ul><li><p><code>_soil_module</code>: describes an empirical relationship between the total water potential and relative water content of soil.</p></li><li><p><code>_air_module</code>: describes the relationship between the total water potential and water potential of air.</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Hydraulic conductivity</p><ul><li><p><code>K_module</code>: describes hydraulic conductivity as proportional to the cross area of the compartment. </p></li><li><p><code>constant_K_module</code>: describes a constant hydraulic conductivity.</p></li></ul></li><li><p>Connection modules</p><ul><li><p><code>hydraulic_connection</code>: describes a water flow between two compartments based on the specific hydraulic conductivities of those compartments.</p></li><li><p><code>daynight_hydraulic_connection</code>: describes a water flow between two compartments based on the hydraulic conductivities of those compartments that decreases during night.</p></li><li><p><code>constant_hydraulic_connection</code>: describes a water flow between two compartments and specifies its own hydraulic conductivity.</p></li></ul></li></ul></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>Please note that the carbon dynamics modules are very simplistic and only exist so users can make a model that works out of the box. Users that want to create a realistic model are expected to implement some functional modules of their own in accordance with their own use for the package, as will be discussed next tutorial.</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><h4 id="Mapping-function-to-structure">Mapping function to structure</h4></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>When the functional modules have been defined, we can assign them to the different types of structural module and the connections between them. We can do this for both with a simple <code>Dictionary</code>. Note that, for now, while structural modules can be assigned multiple functional modules, their connections can only be assigned one connection module.</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>module_coupling = Dict(
    :Stem =&gt; [hydraulic_module, constant_carbon_module, K_module],
    :Leaf =&gt; [hydraulic_module, simple_photosynthesis_module, K_module],
    :Soil =&gt; [environmental_module, _soil_module, constant_K_module],
    :Air =&gt; [environmental_module, _air_module, constant_K_module]
);</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>connecting_modules = Dict(
    (:Soil, :Stem) =&gt; hydraulic_connection,
    (:Stem, :Stem) =&gt; hydraulic_connection,
    (:Stem, :Leaf) =&gt; hydraulic_connection,
    (:Leaf, :Air) =&gt; daynight_hydraulic_connection,
);</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>plantcoupling = PlantCoupling(; module_coupling, connecting_modules);</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><h4 id="Defining-parameter-and-initial-values">Defining parameter and initial values</h4></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>Next to the equations themselves, an important part in describing the plant's functional processes is defining the equations' parameter - and initial values. Since we'll restrict ourselves to hydraulic equations for this tutorial, these parameters and variables are the ones described in the section <a href="nothinghere">Theoretical overview</a>.</p><p>In PlantModules, parameter - and initial values are defined in a hierarchical manner, here listed in ascending priority:</p><blockquote><p><strong>Model-wide default values &lt; module-specific default values &lt; node-specific values</strong></p></blockquote><p>For our current example, this means that there is no point in specifying the initial values for the compartment dimensions <em>D</em> for our Leaf compartments in the module-specific default values or the model-wide default values, since we already defined these values in all of the Leaf nodes of the graph, which have the highest priority.</p></div>

<div class="markdown"><p>Finally, all parameter changes are wrapped in the <code>PlantParameters</code> struct.</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>plantparams = PlantParameters(; default_changes, module_defaults, connection_values);</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><h3 id="Bringing-it-all-together">Bringing it all together</h3></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>Now that we have all parts of our model defined, all that's left to do is putting it together. For this we use the main workhorse of PlantModules: <code>generate_system</code>.</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>system = generate_system(plantstructure, plantcoupling, plantparams);</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><p>This function will generate the <code>ODESystem</code> describing the model. It is possible to fine-tune the model even further at this stage as described in the <a href="nothinghere">Customizing the model</a> section of the docs, thought this should generally not be required.</p></div>


<div class="markdown"><h2 id="Running-the-model">Running the model</h2></div>


<div class="markdown"><p>Running the model is taken care of DifferentialEquations.jl. Users that are unfamiliar with the package may want to take a brief look at <a href="https://docs.sciml.ai/DiffEqDocs/stable/">the DifferentialEquations.jl docs</a>.</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>time_span = (0.0, 48.0);</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>prob = ODEProblem(system, [], time_span, sparse = true, use_scc = false);</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><div class="admonition is-warning"><header class="admonition-header">Warning</header><div class="admonition-body"><p>Problem construction currently throws an error if a <code>SciMLBase.SCCNonlinearProblem</code> is used for the initialization problem. We can prevent this by specifying <code>use_scc = false</code>.</p></div></div></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>sol = solve(prob);</code></pre>



<div class="markdown"><p>In order to compare the results of higher transpiration, we remake and solve the problem with lower relative air humidity. This can be done by repeating the parameter, problem, system and solution definition with a different value for <code>W_r</code>, or we can simply use <code>ModelingToolkit.jl</code>'s <code>remake</code> function. To make it easier to get the correct variable from our system with many subsystems, the <code>get_subsystem_variables</code> convenience function exists that extract all variables corresponding to a certain name and structural module (or connection between two).</p></div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>air_W_r = get_subsystem_variables(system, plantstructure, :W_r, :Air)[1]</code></pre>
